WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.390 --> 00:00:01.765
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
Part of what I

00:00:01.765 --> 00:00:03.570
do is work with people
who are preparing

00:00:03.570 --> 00:00:06.170
to be K-12 art teachers.

00:00:06.170 --> 00:00:08.140
I actually work with artists.

00:00:08.140 --> 00:00:13.230
I've taught studio-based
courses in ceramics, drawing.

00:00:13.230 --> 00:00:15.740
And I'm also working
with grad students who

00:00:15.740 --> 00:00:19.950
are interested in engaging
in research about and through

00:00:19.950 --> 00:00:23.860
and within art practices,
visual cultural practices.

00:00:23.860 --> 00:00:29.070
So there's this range of
folks with whom I'm working.

00:00:29.070 --> 00:00:30.300
So one of your--

00:00:30.300 --> 00:00:32.592
I'm trying to negotiate
a place to enter, Larry.

00:00:32.592 --> 00:00:34.050
And one of the
things that you said

00:00:34.050 --> 00:00:40.030
was how explicit am I with,
as we've been calling it,

00:00:40.030 --> 00:00:43.607
this hidden agenda,
a hidden curriculum?

00:00:43.607 --> 00:00:44.940
LARRY SUSSKIND: Not as an agenda

00:00:44.940 --> 00:00:46.480
STEPHEN CARPENTER: No, but
it's the same thing, right?

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:48.170
In many cases, it's
the same thing, right?

00:00:48.170 --> 00:00:49.740
Because you have an agenda
that you're trying to cover,

00:00:49.740 --> 00:00:51.870
whether it's an
official agenda, we

00:00:51.870 --> 00:00:55.640
can correlate that to
the official curriculum.

00:00:55.640 --> 00:00:59.190
And I'm pulling this term,
these curriculum pieces

00:00:59.190 --> 00:01:01.860
from the work of George
Posner and others,

00:01:01.860 --> 00:01:05.670
where you might consider there
are five kinds of curriculum

00:01:05.670 --> 00:01:08.726
that are happening at
the same time, five

00:01:08.726 --> 00:01:09.600
concurrent curricula.

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:12.660
He says there's the
official curriculum, which

00:01:12.660 --> 00:01:13.660
is what is written down.

00:01:13.660 --> 00:01:14.910
It's that officially mandated.

00:01:14.910 --> 00:01:16.384
This is what will be taught.

00:01:16.384 --> 00:01:18.300
Then there there's the
operational curriculum.

00:01:18.300 --> 00:01:22.570
It's what you put into practice,
trying to operationalize it.

00:01:22.570 --> 00:01:25.380
So it would be the
official agenda, then

00:01:25.380 --> 00:01:27.200
the operationalized agenda.

00:01:27.200 --> 00:01:30.280
So agenda and curriculum to
me, agenda gets a bad rap,

00:01:30.280 --> 00:01:31.530
I think, just like propaganda.

00:01:31.530 --> 00:01:33.280
But that's a different
kettle of horses.

00:01:33.280 --> 00:01:33.780
OK.

00:01:33.780 --> 00:01:36.180
So then the third curriculum
that Posner talks about

00:01:36.180 --> 00:01:41.070
is the hidden curriculum,
what is not official,

00:01:41.070 --> 00:01:43.980
what is not officially
written down and intended,

00:01:43.980 --> 00:01:47.670
and what also is not necessarily
operationalized intentionally.

00:01:47.670 --> 00:01:50.610
But it is what is hidden
and gets learned and taught

00:01:50.610 --> 00:01:51.720
at the same time.

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:54.420
The fourth would then
be the null curriculum,

00:01:54.420 --> 00:01:56.670
what is not taught, what is
not intended to be taught,

00:01:56.670 --> 00:01:59.630
what is absent and
explicitly missing.

00:01:59.630 --> 00:02:01.380
And then the fifth is
the extracurriculum.

00:02:01.380 --> 00:02:04.330
It doesn't happen inside
those intentional spaces

00:02:04.330 --> 00:02:07.080
that we might think is
formalized schooling.

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:09.169
So if we think of-- you're
on the volleyball team.

00:02:09.169 --> 00:02:11.970
That's extracurricular, but it's
still related to that education

00:02:11.970 --> 00:02:12.480
space.

00:02:12.480 --> 00:02:15.070
All five of those things
are happening all the time.

00:02:15.070 --> 00:02:20.611
So the hidden agenda, the hidden
curriculum is one that I--

00:02:20.611 --> 00:02:22.860
and there's some tension
there, because in some cases,

00:02:22.860 --> 00:02:27.150
it's operationalized with
a conscious awareness

00:02:27.150 --> 00:02:27.907
that it's hidden.

00:02:27.907 --> 00:02:29.490
I'm not going to be
explicit about it.

00:02:29.490 --> 00:02:31.380
But then there can be
a hidden curriculum

00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:33.450
where it's being
taught and learned

00:02:33.450 --> 00:02:37.220
without the intention of it
being taught and learned.

00:02:37.220 --> 00:02:40.020
So when we ask kids to--

00:02:40.020 --> 00:02:42.730
for example, there
are bathrooms--

00:02:42.730 --> 00:02:45.300
when I was a kid,
gendered bathrooms,

00:02:45.300 --> 00:02:47.470
men's bathroom when
we're boys and girls,

00:02:47.470 --> 00:02:49.470
and so it's teaching us
certain things about how

00:02:49.470 --> 00:02:51.450
society is structured.

00:02:51.450 --> 00:02:53.670
But when we move
and have a shift

00:02:53.670 --> 00:02:56.190
in our cultural and social
space where bathrooms

00:02:56.190 --> 00:02:59.580
don't have to have certain
labels, then other knowledge,

00:02:59.580 --> 00:03:02.680
other ideas are taught and
learned through those gestures.

00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:04.765
But they're not
necessarily official.

00:03:04.765 --> 00:03:05.640
Does that make sense?

00:03:05.640 --> 00:03:06.410
LARRY SUSSKIND: Yeah.

00:03:06.410 --> 00:03:07.326
STEPHEN CARPENTER: OK.

00:03:07.326 --> 00:03:11.360
So the program where I teach
at Penn State for an art

00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:15.634
education, also at VCFA,
we're very explicit about what

00:03:15.634 --> 00:03:16.800
that hidden agenda might be.

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:18.330
It's to the point where
it's not hidden at all.

00:03:18.330 --> 00:03:19.490
It's very upfront.

00:03:19.490 --> 00:03:20.460
It's very official.

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:21.960
And it gets
operationalized in terms

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:26.940
of a focus on social justice,
a focus on the role of artists

00:03:26.940 --> 00:03:30.060
and art in the world
and what matters matter

00:03:30.060 --> 00:03:38.160
and how we can engage
with concepts and theories

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:40.740
like we heard in the
introduction-- feminist theory

00:03:40.740 --> 00:03:43.950
or critical race theory
or critical pedagogy.

00:03:43.950 --> 00:03:47.580
Or we can think about
anti-racist theory.

00:03:47.580 --> 00:03:50.230
So we can think about--
or disability studies--

00:03:50.230 --> 00:03:54.910
all of these different ways
in which society operates

00:03:54.910 --> 00:03:59.450
are part of the
curriculum that I've

00:03:59.450 --> 00:04:01.820
been part of in these
two institutions

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:03.860
to look at the
preparation of teachers.

00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:08.060
So someone who says, hey, I want
to go study in this program,

00:04:08.060 --> 00:04:09.800
it's not a surprise
to them when we

00:04:09.800 --> 00:04:14.450
start talking about feminist
pedagogy and feminist issues.

00:04:14.450 --> 00:04:17.000
What might be a
surprise is perhaps

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:19.529
the ways in which we approach
that and then operationalize

00:04:19.529 --> 00:04:20.029
it.

00:04:20.029 --> 00:04:21.740
But it shouldn't be a surprise.

00:04:21.740 --> 00:04:26.930
Now in some cases, some
people might not always

00:04:26.930 --> 00:04:30.360
read the [LAUGHS]
the fine print.

00:04:30.360 --> 00:04:32.700
And then there might
be a surprise there.

00:04:32.700 --> 00:04:35.470
But I don't hide those issues.

00:04:35.470 --> 00:04:40.580
As a matter of fact, I'm very
upfront with my undergraduates

00:04:40.580 --> 00:04:46.710
about, in this course, we're
going to learn about learning.

00:04:46.710 --> 00:04:49.921
And I'm more interested in
learning than I am in teaching.

00:04:49.921 --> 00:04:51.420
And that doesn't
make sense to a lot

00:04:51.420 --> 00:04:53.610
of people who are preparing
to be teachers or think

00:04:53.610 --> 00:04:58.140
about teaching, because to
frame it around learning

00:04:58.140 --> 00:05:00.540
suggests there's a shift from
the agency of the teacher

00:05:00.540 --> 00:05:03.960
as the primary vehicle
to the student.

00:05:03.960 --> 00:05:06.540
LARRY SUSSKIND: Do I
need a first course

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:09.090
where there's no
interference with learning

00:05:09.090 --> 00:05:12.480
to draw in a basic way?

00:05:12.480 --> 00:05:16.800
And then after that, I can come
to a second level drawing class

00:05:16.800 --> 00:05:19.530
where you can lay on
all this other stuff.

00:05:19.530 --> 00:05:23.550
Or from the very
beginning, in even the most

00:05:23.550 --> 00:05:26.700
rudimentary learning
of the medium,

00:05:26.700 --> 00:05:32.430
are you already insinuating into
the design of this curriculum

00:05:32.430 --> 00:05:34.150
this other set of concerns?

00:05:34.150 --> 00:05:36.480
I don't even have
to know anything

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:40.080
about the basics independent
of this second concern

00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:42.780
to start learning this
other set of things?

00:05:42.780 --> 00:05:43.860
STEPHEN CARPENTER: No.

00:05:43.860 --> 00:05:46.007
One can enter with the concerns.

00:05:46.007 --> 00:05:48.340
LARRY SUSSKIND: And that is
your plan, most of the time?

00:05:48.340 --> 00:05:49.020
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
All of the time.

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:49.560
LARRY SUSSKIND: All the time.

00:05:49.560 --> 00:05:49.980
STEPHEN CARPENTER: All the time.

00:05:49.980 --> 00:05:51.063
LARRY SUSSKIND: All right.

00:05:51.063 --> 00:05:53.970
STEPHEN CARPENTER: So [CHUCKLES]
we start with, let's say,

00:05:53.970 --> 00:05:56.130
social issues.

00:05:56.130 --> 00:06:01.410
Or let's say we're grounding the
course within a social space.

00:06:01.410 --> 00:06:03.180
We all live in a social space.

00:06:03.180 --> 00:06:04.680
We all come with
a set of concerns.

00:06:04.680 --> 00:06:07.920
We all come with a
set of experiences.

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:13.690
We come to the studio, and
then return to wherever

00:06:13.690 --> 00:06:15.100
we were before that.

00:06:17.890 --> 00:06:20.290
What we experience
outside of the studio

00:06:20.290 --> 00:06:22.090
is content for art-making.

00:06:22.090 --> 00:06:25.580
It's content for
engagement through art.

00:06:25.580 --> 00:06:28.750
So this is a shift
where we think of--

00:06:32.020 --> 00:06:37.420
so if we take a step back
to notions of curriculum,

00:06:37.420 --> 00:06:41.350
a very basic question in
curriculum design, creating

00:06:41.350 --> 00:06:44.470
theory, curriculum
development, I should say,

00:06:44.470 --> 00:06:48.130
is what is worth knowing?

00:06:48.130 --> 00:06:50.360
What content do we
want students to learn?

00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:51.970
What is worth knowing?

00:06:51.970 --> 00:06:53.720
We might then look
through the progression

00:06:53.720 --> 00:06:54.594
of curriculum theory.

00:06:54.594 --> 00:06:59.480
And then folks 30,
40 years ago start

00:06:59.480 --> 00:07:00.770
making a shift in [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:00.770 --> 00:07:02.000
What is worthwhile?

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:03.440
What matters?

00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:05.990
And what happens is
there's a movement away

00:07:05.990 --> 00:07:08.990
from a more modernist
notion of art

00:07:08.990 --> 00:07:12.530
as material-based to art as
a reflection and engagement

00:07:12.530 --> 00:07:13.520
within the world.

00:07:13.520 --> 00:07:16.070
Not that it hadn't
been that way before.

00:07:16.070 --> 00:07:20.290
But that the world becomes
an art-making medium,

00:07:20.290 --> 00:07:25.490
and in a context that can be
not only reflected and depicted,

00:07:25.490 --> 00:07:28.250
but can also be used
as one of the materials

00:07:28.250 --> 00:07:30.470
within art-making practice.

00:07:30.470 --> 00:07:32.180
And that art practice
can have some sort

00:07:32.180 --> 00:07:37.280
of engaged and intentional
effect within that.

00:07:37.280 --> 00:07:41.630
So the kind of drawing
class that you're mentioning

00:07:41.630 --> 00:07:44.540
or describing is not uncommon.

00:07:44.540 --> 00:07:47.180
These kinds of courses
happen quite often.

00:07:47.180 --> 00:07:52.400
But their titles don't
always reflect that.

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:54.452
And many art schools
are making some shifts.

00:07:54.452 --> 00:07:56.660
I had mentioned to a colleague
a number of years ago,

00:07:56.660 --> 00:07:59.090
I said, we really need to
change the names of some

00:07:59.090 --> 00:07:59.840
of these courses.

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:05.450
Like, we should have Art with
Larry, Art 505, Art with Larry,

00:08:05.450 --> 00:08:07.820
and then Art 507,
Art with Steve.

00:08:07.820 --> 00:08:11.180
And they would have a sense
of what that course was about.

00:08:11.180 --> 00:08:14.600
It it's not a materials-specific
course, although it could be.

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:19.580
But when we move the focus
to issues, ideas, concerns,

00:08:19.580 --> 00:08:26.790
engagements, problems, ideas,
that is an easier entry

00:08:26.790 --> 00:08:29.940
point for the kinds of pedagogy
that we're talking about,

00:08:29.940 --> 00:08:34.370
that lend themselves
to the sensibilities

00:08:34.370 --> 00:08:38.190
of disruptive practices,
of social consciousness,

00:08:38.190 --> 00:08:40.140
of transformative learning.

00:08:40.140 --> 00:08:43.020
LARRY SUSSKIND: And what
I've taken from your comments

00:08:43.020 --> 00:08:49.050
on occasion is that I ought
to have that objective if I'm

00:08:49.050 --> 00:08:55.140
going to teach people about
operating in their community.

00:08:55.140 --> 00:08:59.850
Don't just teach the
method or the content.

00:08:59.850 --> 00:09:05.280
But get to this other level and
build that into the curriculum.

00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:06.690
Take responsibility for that.

00:09:06.690 --> 00:09:07.770
Be explicit about it.

00:09:07.770 --> 00:09:11.684
Be accountable not just
during but even before,

00:09:11.684 --> 00:09:14.100
although who knows whether
they would have let me anywhere

00:09:14.100 --> 00:09:18.490
near the place if I had
said at the beginning,

00:09:18.490 --> 00:09:20.865
our goal here is to bring
about change in this community.

00:09:20.865 --> 00:09:23.323
STEPHEN CARPENTER: Well, it
depends on your strategy there,

00:09:23.323 --> 00:09:24.006
right?

00:09:24.006 --> 00:09:25.380
So if we think
about it this way.

00:09:25.380 --> 00:09:28.530
Now you didn't mention
this in your story.

00:09:28.530 --> 00:09:30.600
But I would be interested
in this component,

00:09:30.600 --> 00:09:33.390
because it also then
gets back to one

00:09:33.390 --> 00:09:36.210
of those parts of the
longer question you asked me

00:09:36.210 --> 00:09:38.970
earlier about my own
students and my own teaching.

00:09:41.660 --> 00:09:43.887
This is part of the
social studies curriculum?

00:09:43.887 --> 00:09:44.720
LARRY SUSSKIND: Yes.

00:09:44.720 --> 00:09:46.370
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
Officially, right?

00:09:46.370 --> 00:09:47.990
There should be some objectives.

00:09:47.990 --> 00:09:50.450
There should be some state
standards or district standards

00:09:50.450 --> 00:09:53.630
or district objectives
that many teachers

00:09:53.630 --> 00:09:55.045
consider to be the curriculum.

00:09:55.045 --> 00:09:56.420
And they teach to
those standards

00:09:56.420 --> 00:09:58.040
or to those objectives.

00:09:58.040 --> 00:10:01.040
I teach my students,
put those aside.

00:10:01.040 --> 00:10:04.310
Let's build on what you
know, what is most important,

00:10:04.310 --> 00:10:06.664
build on your own
politics, build on the--

00:10:06.664 --> 00:10:09.080
let's start with the themes
and the ideas and the concerns

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:09.920
that you have.

00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:12.080
Build your curriculum
around that,

00:10:12.080 --> 00:10:15.410
drawing on your art practice,
your knowledge of art.

00:10:15.410 --> 00:10:17.570
And then let's compare.

00:10:17.570 --> 00:10:20.570
Let's use those standards
or those objectives

00:10:20.570 --> 00:10:22.770
as an assessment.

00:10:22.770 --> 00:10:24.560
Now how many of
those do we address?

00:10:24.560 --> 00:10:26.899
Usually we can
cover all of those.

00:10:26.899 --> 00:10:28.440
But if we start the
other way around,

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:31.004
we start with learning Objective
6 and learning Objective 8,

00:10:31.004 --> 00:10:32.420
and this is the
lesson, it's going

00:10:32.420 --> 00:10:33.676
to be really narrow and tight.

00:10:33.676 --> 00:10:36.050
And it doesn't-- and you're
always going to be interested

00:10:36.050 --> 00:10:37.920
in we got to kick it
back into the center.

00:10:37.920 --> 00:10:39.290
We got to make sure they're--

00:10:39.290 --> 00:10:43.100
But in the way that you
did it, I would imagine

00:10:43.100 --> 00:10:45.500
you could have said
at any given moment,

00:10:45.500 --> 00:10:47.390
when you felt some
resistance, well,

00:10:47.390 --> 00:10:49.700
if we look at the
standards, we're

00:10:49.700 --> 00:10:52.940
covering XYZ, 1, 2, 3,
4, 5, 6 7, because--

00:10:52.940 --> 00:10:54.540
and this is a way that one--

00:10:54.540 --> 00:10:58.190
I'm not trying to say this is
how you do a cover-up story.

00:10:58.190 --> 00:11:01.680
But this is how you can
justify the social practice,

00:11:01.680 --> 00:11:06.030
social engagement, social
consciousness pedagogy

00:11:06.030 --> 00:11:09.600
is you say, look, we're
meeting all of the standards.

00:11:09.600 --> 00:11:11.747
As a matter of fact, if
we were to do, let's say,

00:11:11.747 --> 00:11:13.830
three units like this over
the course of the year,

00:11:13.830 --> 00:11:17.017
we could hit all of those
objectives each time.

00:11:17.017 --> 00:11:18.850
If we do it in a more
conventional approach,

00:11:18.850 --> 00:11:21.420
we might only address one
of those objectives once

00:11:21.420 --> 00:11:24.180
or a few of them
very superficially.

00:11:24.180 --> 00:11:30.060
So this becomes an even more
potent way to make a case,

00:11:30.060 --> 00:11:31.975
because you're using the--

00:11:31.975 --> 00:11:33.225
you were talking about values.

00:11:33.225 --> 00:11:34.740
LARRY SUSSKIND: Use the
objectives against them.

00:11:34.740 --> 00:11:35.390
[LAUGHING]

00:11:35.390 --> 00:11:37.929
STEPHEN CARPENTER: Yes,
I call it playing judo.

00:11:37.929 --> 00:11:40.470
You use your opponent's strength
and speed to your advantage.

00:11:40.470 --> 00:11:40.980
LARRY SUSSKIND: Right.

00:11:40.980 --> 00:11:41.200
STEPHEN CARPENTER: Yeah.

00:11:41.850 --> 00:11:43.933
LARRY SUSSKIND: When I
teach graduate students who

00:11:43.933 --> 00:11:47.010
are in a professional
degree program, all of this

00:11:47.010 --> 00:11:49.740
is easily talked about.

00:11:49.740 --> 00:11:52.980
It's layered into the social
